text:
A more accurate translation for this title: "Why do we have curiosity and a desire to think for ourselves?" Conspiracy theories are ideas that spring up when there is no satisfactory explanation of what is happening. They also arise when there is no transparency and no desire for authorities and governments to support the common good.

When people perceive that they are being lied to and their options and freedoms are being limited or even trampled upon, then they stop trusting the governments and authorities. Would you still trust a government that gave order to beat up your family for taking part in a peaceful protest or took away your job if you didn't take a new experimental vaccine?

People are not cattle. We think for ourselves and we can come up with our own conclusions. Granted, some of those conclusions might be wrong. But it's our right to consider them rather than accepting government narratives that are politically motivated most often AGAINST THE PEOPLE. A Princeton study in the US showed that 90% of people have zero influence on government policy. Knowing that, why would the people blindly support ideas that the government says are true without a(n unbiased) third party verification?

Children don't always listen to their parents, and not all parents are kindhearted and supportive. Some are alcoholics who only hurt their children.. And just as children have the right to go on their own paths, choose what they dream about and make mistakes before learning a subject in school, people have the right to come up with the craziest, most illogical ideas on their path to learning the truth. They teach us to think for ourselves. THAT is why we love conspiracy theories.. Peace to all! <3 :)
